    Date: 19 Apr 88 12:59:47 EST (Tue)
    From: mark@cblpf.ATT.COM (Mark Horton)

    One possible reason why there are so many variations is that UNIX is a
    registered trademark of AT&amp;T.  It may be a violation of trademark law
    to say in an HINFO field that your machine runs "UNIX"...
    This is in fact the reason why names like Xenix, SunOS, AIX, and so on
    are the product names - AT&amp;T won't let them call their product UNIX.
    (The upcoming venture with Microsoft will be the first.)

    Maybe it would be safer to call them POSIX, I'll bet IEEE won't mind.

Will this "POSIX" have the same file syntax as Unix?

For those of you who think this is pedantic distinction, I do use a
machine which makes use of the OS type in order to figure out, for
instance, what sort of filesystem operations are permitted.  So I am
very interested in getting a consistent set of names in that field.
Call it "POS" for all I care, as long as everybody calls it that.

I don't see any advantage, beyond historical accident, to CPU type any
more.  The PDP-10 names are no longer consistent either.

